{"id":"1812.03081","submitter":"Anatoly Vershik M","authors":"A.Vershik","title":"Three theorems on the uniqueness of the Plancherel measure from\n  different viewpoints","comments":"22 pages,Ref.38","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.FA math.RT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider three uniqueness theorems: one from the theory of meromorphic\nfunctions, another one from asymptotic combinatorics, and the third one about\nrepresentations of the infinite symmetric group.\n  The first theorem establishes the uniqueness of the function~$\\exp z$ in a\nclass of entire functions. The second one is about the uniqueness of a random\nmonotone nondegenerate numbering of the two-dimensional lattice~$\\Bbb Z^2_+$,\nor of a nondegenerate central measure on the space of infinite Young tableaux.\nAnd the third theorem establishes the uniqueness of a representation of the\ninfinite symmetric group~${\\frak S}_{\\infty}$ whose restrictions to finite\nsubgroups have vanishingly few invariant vectors.\n  But in fact all three theorems are, up to a nontrivial rephrasing of\nconditions from one area of mathematics in terms of another area, the same\ntheorem! Up to now, researchers working in each of these areas were not aware\nof this equivalence. The parallelism of these uniqueness theorems on the one\nhand, and the difference of their proofs on the other hand call for a deeper\nanalysis of the nature of uniqueness and suggest to transfer the methods of\nproof between the areas.\n  More exactly, each of these theorems establishes the uniqueness of the\nso-called Plancherel measure, which is the main object of our paper. In\nparticular, we show that this notion is general for all locally finite groups.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 7 Dec 2018 16:05:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 16 Dec 2018 15:31:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-12-18"}
